  <h1>{frontmatter.title}</h1>

  <p>
    When we started 3D3D, the vision was clear: connect local makers with customers who need custom 3D printed parts. Makers already own printers. They already know how to use them. What they need is a steady stream of work without the hassle of finding customers, handling invoicing, and managing support.
  </p>

  <h2>The Network Approach</h2>

  <p>
    We started in Moncton — our home base. Local maker spaces, Facebook groups for 3D printing enthusiasts, Reddit's r/3Dprinting and r/newbrunswick. The first makers came from personal referrals and community outreach.
  </p>

  <p>
    From there, we expanded city by city. Halifax and Fredericton came next, then St. John's and Charlottetown. Each city had its own maker community with different dynamics. Halifax had a strong pool of hobbyist printers. St. John's had fewer makers but higher average capacity per maker.
  </p>

  <p>
    The network grows through reputation. Makers tell other makers. Customers spread the word when they get quality parts quickly. Organic growth has been more effective than any advertising campaign.
  </p>

  <h2>Quality Standards</h2>

  <p>
    Not everyone with a printer qualifies. Our onboarding process includes:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Print quality test:</strong> Three calibration prints evaluated for dimensional accuracy, surface finish, and layer adhesion.</li>
    <li><strong>Material verification:</strong> Makers must demonstrate competency with at least PLA and PETG. TPU, ABS, and ASA are optional certifications.</li>
    <li><strong>Turnaround commitment:</strong> 24-hour print start time, 48-hour ship time for standard orders.</li>
    <li><strong>Equipment inventory:</strong> We track each maker's printer models, build volumes, and material stock.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These standards ensure customers get consistent quality regardless of which maker handles their order. The network's reputation depends on every member delivering reliable results.
  </p>

  <h2>The Network Today</h2>

  <p>
    As of March 2026, the network includes makers across all four Atlantic provinces. Most orders can be fulfilled by a maker within 100km of the customer. This cuts shipping time and cost dramatically compared to centralized fulfillment from Toronto or Montreal.
  </p>

  <p>
    The geographic distribution is intentional. Local production means faster delivery. It means supporting regional economies. It means understanding local needs — from fishing boat parts in Newfoundland to agricultural components in the Annapolis Valley.
  </p>

  <h2>Beyond Orders: Event-Based Printing</h2>

  <p>
    The network also supports our event services. Content creator Wess runs live 3D printing demonstrations at festivals, markets, and conventions throughout Atlantic Canada. These events introduce 3D printing to new audiences and drive traffic back to network makers.
  </p>

  <p>
    When someone sees a printer in action at a local market, they're more likely to order custom parts later. The event presence builds trust and awareness that traditional advertising can't match.
  </p>

  <h2>Join the Network</h2>

  <p>
    We're always looking for quality-focused makers to join the network. If you run a 3D printer in Atlantic Canada (or anywhere in Canada — we're expanding), <a href="/makers">apply to join</a>. The application takes 5 minutes and we'll schedule a print quality review within a week.
  </p>

  <p>
    The network continues to grow. More makers means faster turnaround, broader geographic coverage, and deeper material expertise. If you print quality parts and want consistent work, we'd love to hear from you.
  </p>
